    "role": "user",
    "content": "FILES:\n- Reference graph: \"/home/user/Julia/synthetic_cities/philadelphia_level1.json\"\n- Reference road lengths: \"/home/user/Julia/synthetic_cities/philadelphia_road_length.csv\"\n- Output directory: \"/home/user/Julia/synthetic_cities/philadelpia_rslts\"\n- Output graph: \"phil_graph_X.json\" (where X is the next available ID)\n- Output road lengths: \"phil_length_X.csv\" (where X is the next available ID)\n\nBEFORE STARTING:\n1. Check the output directory \"/home/user/Julia/synthetic_cities/philadelpia_rslts/\"\n2. Count existing .json files to determine the next ID\n3. If there are 7 .json files, use ID = 8\n4. Create files: phil_rslts_8.json and phil_rslts_8.csv\n\nPURPOSE:\nThe generated graph will serve as a seed for Voronoi diagram generation. The graph structure should form POLYGONS (closed regions) that will become Voronoi cells. The graph must be primarily polygon-based, though a few dead ends or single lines extending from the main structure are acceptable.\n\nCRITICAL GRAPH REQUIREMENTS:\n1. CONNECTED: The graph MUST be fully connected - every node must be reachable from every other node. NO isolated nodes or disconnected components allowed.\n2. CLOSED STRUCTURE: The graph must form a CLOSED boundary - it needs an outer ring/perimeter that encloses all internal structure. This is required for Voronoi algorithm.\n3. POLYGON-BASED: Interior should be divided into polygonal cells (closed cycles), not just edges hanging in space.\n4. SIMILAR BUT UNIQUE: Inspired by Philadelphia Downtown district geometry but NOT a copy - create original coordinates and structure.\n\nWORKFLOW (max 30 iterations):\n\n1. Read reference graph file to understand the REAL geometry of Philadelphia Downtown district - study the actual node positions and edge connections. Read reference road lengths to understand edge length distribution. NOTE: The reference graph is NOT planar - it is only an example of the spatial structure. Your synthetic graph MUST be planar.\n\n2. Create a planar graph manually with approximately 40 edges. Base your design on the reference geometry - use similar coordinate ranges and edge length distribution. The synthetic city can be smaller than the reference - focus on quality over size. IMPORTANT: Create ORIGINAL geometry inspired by the reference - do NOT copy the reference coordinates. Generate new, unique node positions that follow similar patterns but are distinctly different.\n\n3. VALIDATE: Call check_planarity(nodes_dict, edges_dict). If \"is_planar\": false, fix and repeat. PLANARITY IS MANDATORY - never proceed with a non-planar graph.\n\n4. VALIDATE: Calculate edge lengths from your nodes, call compare_cities with reference lengths. If Wasserstein metric >= 0.05, adjust and go to step 3. NOTE: 0.06 is TOO HIGH - metric MUST be strictly below 0.05.\n\n5. ONLY when BOTH validations pass (is_planar=true AND metric<0.05): save graph and road lengths to the output directory with the correct ID.\n\nVORONOI-READY STRUCTURE (CRITICAL):\n- The graph MUST be FULLY CONNECTED - no isolated nodes, no disconnected pairs, no separate components\n- The graph MUST have a CLOSED OUTER BOUNDARY - an enclosing perimeter ring\n- Interior must form POLYGONS (closed cycles) - these become Voronoi cells\n- Think of it as a mesh of connected polygonal regions with a closed border\n- Most nodes should be part of at least one polygon/cycle\n- A few dead ends (degree-1 nodes) are acceptable but should be rare\n- Avoid long chains that don't form closed regions\n- Good structures: honeycomb-like, irregular triangulation, nested polygons with outer ring\n- Bad structures: pure trees, star graphs, long linear chains, disconnected components, open boundaries\n\nPLANARITY STRATEGY (CRITICAL):\n- Start with a CLOSED OUTER RING first, then add internal divisions\n- Add edges ONE AT A TIME and check planarity after each addition\n- If adding an edge breaks planarity, don't add it - try a different edge\n- Safe patterns: outer boundary + internal triangulation, nested polygons\n- NEVER create edges that cross existing edges geometrically\n\nADJUSTMENT STRATEGY:\n- You don't need to regenerate the entire graph each iteration\n- Make small targeted modifications: move single nodes, add/remove individual edges\n- If planarity fails: remove the specific crossing edge reported in the error\n- If metric too high: adjust node positions to change edge lengths, or add/remove edges\n- If metric is 0.06, you're close - small adjustments to edge lengths should fix it\n\nVALIDATION RULES:\n- MUST call check_planarity - if \"is_planar\": false, graph is INVALID\n- MUST call compare_cities - if metric >= 0.05, graph is INVALID (0.06 is NOT acceptable)\n- NEVER save until both validations pass\n- Max 30 attempts, then report failure\n\nREALISM REQUIREMENTS:\n- Study the reference file geometry carefully - mimic its edge length distribution\n- Create ORIGINAL node positions - do NOT copy coordinates from the reference\n- The graph should look SIMILAR to Philadelphia Downtown but be UNIQUE - same style, different coordinates\n- NO perfect grids or lattices - add small random offsets to coordinates\n- MUST have junctions: nodes with degree 3 or 4 (where multiple roads meet)\n- A chain of degree-2 nodes is NOT realistic\n- Target approximately 40 edges\n- Structure should form CLOSED POLYGONS suitable for Voronoi seeding\n\nFORMAT: {\"level1\": [[[x1,y1], ...], [[1,2], [2,3], ...]]}\n\nIMPORTANT:\n- Generate dictionaries manually with numbers, not strings\n- Metric value MUST be below 0.05 (0.06 is too high, 0.04 is good)\n- CSV file has float values - read as numeric\n- ALWAYS calculate metrics from YOUR graph, don't copy reference lengths\n- All data types are float - if you read it as string, the function doesn't work\n- PLANARITY FIRST: A small planar graph is better than a large non-planar one\n- ORIGINALITY: Create new geometry inspired by Philadelphia Downtown, don't duplicate it\n- CONNECTIVITY: Every node must be reachable - no isolated components\n- CLOSED BOUNDARY: Graph must have an enclosing outer ring for Voronoi generation\n- POLYGON STRUCTURE: Graph must form closed regions for Voronoi generation\n- FILE NAMING: Check existing files and use next available ID (e.g., if 7 files exist, use ID 8)"
